<%# ───────────────────────────── CONFIG DASHBOARD ───────────────────────────── %>

<h2>Current Configuration</h2>

<p>
  Three configuration options control error behavior. The values below are read live from
  <code>ReactOnRails.configuration</code> and <code>ReactOnRailsPro.configuration</code> at
  page render time (Rails env: <code><%= Rails.env %></code>).
</p>

<%# ── raise_on_prerender_error ── %>
<div class="config-card">
  <h4>
    <code>ReactOnRails.configuration.raise_on_prerender_error</code> =
    <span class="<%= raise_on_prerender_error ? 'config-val-true' : 'config-val-false' %>"><%= raise_on_prerender_error %></span>
  </h4>
  <p><strong>Gem:</strong> <code>react_on_rails</code> (open-source) &nbsp;|&nbsp;
     <strong>Default:</strong> <code>Rails.env.development?</code> &nbsp;|&nbsp;
     <strong>Set in:</strong> <code>config/initializers/react_on_rails.rb</code></p>

  <div class="history">
    <strong>Why this config exists:</strong>
    When server-side rendering (SSR) fails &mdash; e.g., a component throws during <code>renderToString</code>
    &mdash; React on Rails catches the error on the JS side and returns it as an HTML error message
    (a <code>&lt;pre&gt;</code> tag with the stack trace) along with a <code>hasErrors: true</code> flag.
    Without this config, <strong>that error HTML would silently render into the page</strong>.
    The developer might never notice that SSR failed because the page would still work client-side
    (React hydrates over the error HTML).
    <br/><br/>
    This config was introduced in <strong>Nov 2015</strong> to give developers the choice:
    <strong>should a failed SSR silently degrade</strong> (render error HTML inline and hope the client
    recovers), <strong>or should it loudly fail</strong> (raise <code>PrerenderError</code> so you know
    immediately)?
    <br/><br/>
    Originally it defaulted to <code>false</code> (silent degradation). In <strong>Dec 2018</strong>
    (PR #1145), the default was changed to <code>Rails.env.development?</code> &mdash; the idea being that
    <strong>during development, you want to see SSR errors immediately</strong> so you can fix them before
    they reach production. In production, the default is <code>false</code> so a broken component degrades
    gracefully rather than crashing the entire page.
    <br/><br/>
    This was the <em>only</em> error-related config for 6 years, until <code>throw_js_errors</code> was
    added in 2021 to address a different concern (error tracking).
  </div>

  <p><strong>What it controls (Ruby side):</strong> Whether Rails raises <code>ReactOnRails::PrerenderError</code>
     when the JSON result from JS contains <code>hasErrors: true</code>. This is a Ruby-only config &mdash;
     it does <em>not</em> get passed to JavaScript. Can be overridden per-component:
     <code>react_component("Foo", raise_on_prerender_error: true)</code>.</p>

  <table border="1" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.85em;">
    <tr style="background: #f0f0f0;">
      <th>Value</th>
      <th>Non-streaming (<code>react_component</code>)</th>
      <th>Streaming: shell error (<code>isShellReady = false</code>)</th>
      <th>Streaming: post-shell error (<code>isShellReady = true</code>)</th>
    </tr>
    <tr<%= ' style="background: #e8f5e9;"'.html_safe unless raise_on_prerender_error %>>
      <td><code>false</code></td>
      <td>Error HTML rendered inline in the page (a <code>&lt;pre&gt;</code> tag with the error message). The page still loads and React can hydrate client-side.</td>
      <td>Error HTML streamed inline. The stream continues.</td>
      <td rowspan="2"><em>Not used &mdash; defers to <code>raise_non_shell_server_rendering_errors</code></em></td>
    </tr>
    <tr<%= ' style="background: #e8f5e9;"'.html_safe if raise_on_prerender_error %>>
      <td><code>true</code></td>
      <td>Rails raises <code>PrerenderError</code>. The app&rsquo;s <code>rescue_from</code> handler decides what to show (e.g., redirect, 500 page).</td>
      <td>Rails raises <code>PrerenderError</code> &rarr; aborts streaming response.</td>
    </tr>
  </table>

  <p>The streaming decision logic in <code>helper.rb</code>:</p>
  <pre>def should_raise_streaming_prerender_error?(chunk_json_result, render_options)
  chunk_json_result["hasErrors"] &&
    (if chunk_json_result["isShellReady"]
       render_options.raise_non_shell_server_rendering_errors  # post-shell errors
     else
       render_options.raise_on_prerender_error                 # shell errors
     end)
end</pre>

  <p>The non-streaming path in <code>helper.rb</code>:</p>
  <pre># For non-streaming react_component:
elsif result["hasErrors"] && render_options.raise_on_prerender_error
  raise_prerender_error(result, react_component_name, props, js_code)
end</pre>
</div>

<%# ── throw_js_errors ── %>
<div class="config-card">
  <h4>
    <code>ReactOnRailsPro.configuration.throw_js_errors</code> =
    <span class="<%= throw_js_errors ? 'config-val-true' : 'config-val-false' %>"><%= throw_js_errors %></span>
  </h4>
  <p><strong>Gem:</strong> <code>react_on_rails_pro</code> &nbsp;|&nbsp;
     <strong>Default:</strong> <code>true</code> &nbsp;|&nbsp;
     <strong>Set in:</strong> <code>config/initializers/react_on_rails_pro.rb</code></p>

  <div class="history">
    <strong>Why this config exists:</strong>
    The open-source <code>raise_on_prerender_error</code> controls what <em>Ruby</em> does after JS returns
    an error. But it cannot control what happens <em>inside</em> the Node renderer process itself.
    <br/><br/>
    When a component throws during rendering, the JS error handler has two choices:
    <strong>(1)</strong> catch the error and return error HTML with <code>hasErrors: true</code>
    (the original behavior), or
    <strong>(2)</strong> re-throw the error so the Node renderer&rsquo;s process-level error handling catches it.
    <br/><br/>
    <strong>The problem with option (1):</strong> The Node renderer returns a successful HTTP 200 response
    containing error HTML. From the Node renderer&rsquo;s perspective, the request succeeded &mdash;
    <strong>error tracking tools (Sentry, Honeybadger) running on the Node renderer never see the
    exception</strong>. Errors are invisible to production monitoring.
    <br/><br/>
    <strong>Option (2) solves this:</strong> Re-throwing lets the Node renderer catch the error at the
    process level, report it to Sentry/Honeybadger via <code>errorReporter</code>, and return an
    HTTP error response to Rails.
    <br/><br/>
    Introduced in <strong>Mar 2021</strong> (Pro PR #174 / OSS PR #1365), it originally defaulted to
    <code>false</code> for backwards compatibility. In <strong>Jun 2023</strong> (Pro PR #328), the default
    was changed to <code>true</code> because Pro users almost always want production error visibility.
    <br/><br/>
    <strong>For streaming:</strong> the same idea applies but the mechanism differs. Instead of re-throwing
    (which would crash the render), <code>emitError(error)</code> emits an <code>'error'</code> event on
    the readable stream, which the Node renderer&rsquo;s <code>handleStreamError</code> picks up and
    reports to error tracking.
  </div>

  <p><strong>What it controls (JS side):</strong> This is the <em>only</em> config that is passed from Ruby to
     JavaScript (as the <code>throwJsErrors</code> parameter). It controls behavior differently for
     streaming vs. non-streaming rendering:</p>

  <table border="1" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.85em;">
    <tr style="background: #f0f0f0;">
      <th>Value</th>
      <th>Non-streaming (<code>react_component</code>)</th>
      <th>Streaming (<code>stream_react_component</code>)</th>
      <th>Node renderer errorReporter</th>
    </tr>
    <tr<%= ' style="background: #e8f5e9;"'.html_safe unless throw_js_errors %>>
      <td><code>false</code></td>
      <td>Error caught in JS. Returns error HTML with <code>hasErrors: true</code>. Ruby decides via <code>raise_on_prerender_error</code>.</td>
      <td>Error recorded in <code>renderState.hasErrors</code> and serialized into JSON chunk. No <code>'error'</code> event emitted on the stream.</td>
      <td>NOT called for component errors. Errors are invisible to Sentry/Honeybadger.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr<%= ' style="background: #e8f5e9;"'.html_safe if throw_js_errors %>>
      <td><code>true</code></td>
      <td>Error <strong>re-thrown</strong> in JS. The Node renderer catches it and returns an error HTTP response to Rails. Ruby wraps it as <code>PrerenderError</code> (always raised, regardless of <code>raise_on_prerender_error</code>).</td>
      <td><code>emitError(error)</code> emits an <code>'error'</code> event on the readable stream, in addition to setting <code>renderState.hasErrors</code>.</td>
      <td>Called via <code>handleStreamError</code> in <code>vm.ts</code>. Errors are reported to Sentry/Honeybadger.</td>
    </tr>
  </table>

  <p><em>Note: Infrastructure stream errors in <code>injectRSCPayload.ts</code> emit errors on
     <code>resultStream</code> unconditionally &mdash; they <strong>always</strong> reach
     <code>errorReporter</code> regardless of this setting.</em></p>

  <p>The non-streaming path in <code>serverRenderReactComponent.ts</code>:</p>
  <pre>function handleRenderingError(e, options) {
  if (options.throwJsErrors) {
    throw e;  // Re-thrown → Node renderer returns error HTTP response → Ruby always raises
  }
  // Otherwise: return error HTML inline with hasErrors: true
  return { hasErrors: true, result: handleError(...), error };
}</pre>
</div>

<%# ── raise_non_shell_server_rendering_errors ── %>
<div class="config-card">
  <h4>
    <code>ReactOnRailsPro.configuration.raise_non_shell_server_rendering_errors</code> =
    <span class="<%= raise_non_shell ? 'config-val-true' : 'config-val-false' %>"><%= raise_non_shell %></span>
  </h4>
  <p><strong>Gem:</strong> <code>react_on_rails_pro</code> &nbsp;|&nbsp;
     <strong>Default:</strong> <code>false</code> &nbsp;|&nbsp;
     <strong>Set in:</strong> <code>config/initializers/react_on_rails_pro.rb</code></p>

  <div class="history">
    <strong>Why this config exists:</strong>
    When streaming support was added in <strong>Oct&ndash;Nov 2024</strong>, it introduced a problem that
    <code>raise_on_prerender_error</code> was never designed to handle: <strong>what should happen when an
    error occurs after HTTP headers have already been sent?</strong>
    <br/><br/>
    With non-streaming <code>react_component</code>, the entire render completes before Rails sends any
    response. If it fails, Rails can show an error page, redirect, or render error HTML &mdash; no problem.
    <br/><br/>
    With streaming <code>stream_react_component</code>, Rails sends the HTTP headers and the &ldquo;shell&rdquo;
    (the initial HTML around <code>&lt;Suspense&gt;</code> fallbacks) immediately. Content inside Suspense
    boundaries streams in later as it resolves. If one of those async chunks fails, <strong>Rails has
    already committed to a 200 response</strong>. It cannot redirect. It cannot show a clean error page.
    The only options are:
    <br/><br/>
    <strong>(1) Silently continue</strong> &mdash; embed the error in the JSON chunk metadata
    (<code>hasErrors: true</code>) and let the stream finish. The user sees partial content with the failed
    section either empty or showing an error boundary fallback. This is the default (<code>false</code>)
    because it preserves the rest of the page.
    <br/><br/>
    <strong>(2) Abort the stream</strong> &mdash; raise <code>PrerenderError</code>, which terminates the
    response mid-way. The browser receives a truncated HTML document. This is more disruptive but ensures
    errors are not silently swallowed on the Ruby side.
    <br/><br/>
    The existing <code>raise_on_prerender_error</code> still handles <strong>shell errors</strong>
    (before any HTML is sent), because at that point Rails can still show a proper error response.
    This new config handles only the <strong>post-shell</strong> case where the response is already committed.
  </div>

  <p><strong>What it controls (Ruby side):</strong> Whether Rails raises <code>PrerenderError</code>
     for errors that occur <em>after</em> the shell has already rendered successfully
     (<code>isShellReady = true</code>). These are async errors inside <code>&lt;Suspense&gt;</code>
     boundaries. Ruby-only config. <strong>Only applies to streaming</strong> &mdash; non-streaming
     rendering does not have the concept of shell vs. post-shell.</p>

  <div class="important-note">
    <strong>RSC components are always post-shell:</strong> When a React Server Component is rendered
    via <code>stream_react_component</code> with <code>prerender: true</code>, the component is wrapped
    in <code>RSCProvider &gt; Suspense(fallback=null) &gt; RSCRoute &gt; PromiseWrapper</code>. The
    <code>PromiseWrapper</code> calls React&rsquo;s <code>use(promise)</code> which <strong>suspends</strong>,
    so the shell completes immediately with the Suspense fallback (<code>null</code>). The RSC content
    resolves asynchronously. This means <strong>RSC errors are always classified as post-shell errors</strong>
    (<code>isShellReady = true</code>) and are controlled by this config, <strong>not</strong>
    <code>raise_on_prerender_error</code>.
  </div>

  <table border="1" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.85em;">
    <tr style="background: #f0f0f0;">
      <th>Value</th><th>Post-shell streaming error behavior</th>
    </tr>
    <tr<%= ' style="background: #e8f5e9;"'.html_safe unless raise_non_shell %>>
      <td><code>false</code></td>
      <td>Error silently embedded in JSON chunk (<code>hasErrors: true</code>). Streaming continues. Client sees the error only if it checks the chunk metadata.</td>
    </tr>
    <tr<%= ' style="background: #e8f5e9;"'.html_safe if raise_non_shell %>>
      <td><code>true</code></td>
      <td>Rails raises <code>PrerenderError</code>. Streaming response is aborted. Client receives a truncated response.</td>
    </tr>
  </table>
</div>

<hr/>

<%# ────────────────────── SECTION 1: NON-STREAMING ERRORS ────────────────────── %>

<h2>Section 1: Non-Streaming Errors (<code>react_component</code>)</h2>

<p>
  These use the traditional <code>react_component</code> helper (not streaming).
  The JS code runs via the Node renderer, produces a JSON result with <code>html</code> and
  <code>hasErrors</code>, and Rails decides whether to raise or render inline.
  These pages already exist in the dummy app.
</p>

<div class="scenario">
  <h3>N: Non-streaming error &mdash; <%= link_to "Open page", server_side_log_throw_path(config_params) %></h3>

  <p><span class="label">Component:</span> <code>HelloWorldWithLogAndThrow</code></p>
  <p><span class="label">Helper:</span> <code>react_component</code> (non-streaming) with <code>prerender: true</code></p>
  <p><span class="label">Timing:</span> <strong>Immediate</strong> &mdash; throws synchronously during <code>renderToString</code>.</p>

  <p><strong>View template</strong> (<code>server_side_log_throw.html.erb</code>):</p>
  <pre>&lt;%= react_component("HelloWorldWithLogAndThrow",
    props: @app_props_server_render, prerender: true,
    trace: true, id: "HelloWorldWithLogAndThrow-react-component-0") %&gt;</pre>

  <p><strong>Component source</strong> (<code>HelloWorldWithLogAndThrow.jsx</code>) &mdash; logs to all console levels then throws:</p>
  <pre>const HelloWorldWithLogAndThrow = (_props, _context) => {
  console.log('console.log in HelloWorld');
  console.warn('console.warn in HelloWorld');
  console.error('console.error in HelloWorld');
  throw new Error('throw in HelloWorldWithLogAndThrow');
};</pre>

  <p><strong>Error path</strong> (<code>serverRenderReactComponent.ts</code>):</p>
  <pre>function handleRenderingError(e, options) {
  if (options.throwJsErrors) {    // Currently: <%= throw_js_errors %>
    throw e;                       // <%= throw_js_errors ? "CALLED — error re-thrown in JS" : "NOT taken — throwJsErrors is false" %>
  }
  return { hasErrors: true, result: handleError(...), error };
}</pre>

  <div class="expected-behavior">
    <strong>Expected behavior with current config:</strong><br/>
    <% if throw_js_errors %>
      <span class="label">Browser:</span> The error is <strong>re-thrown in JS</strong> because
      <code>throw_js_errors = true</code>. The Node renderer returns an error HTTP response, and Rails
      wraps it as <code>PrerenderError</code> (always raised when <code>throwJsErrors</code> causes a re-throw,
      regardless of <code>raise_on_prerender_error</code>). The app&rsquo;s <code>rescue_from</code> handler
      redirects to <code>/server_side_log_throw_raise_invoker</code>.<br/>
    <% elsif raise_on_prerender_error %>
      <span class="label">Browser:</span> JS catches the error and returns error HTML with <code>hasErrors: true</code>.
      Rails then raises <code>PrerenderError</code> because <code>raise_on_prerender_error = true</code>.
      The app&rsquo;s <code>rescue_from</code> handler redirects to <code>/server_side_log_throw_raise_invoker</code>.<br/>
    <% else %>
      <span class="label">Browser:</span> JS catches the error and returns error HTML (a <code>&lt;pre&gt;</code> tag
      with the error message). Rails renders it <strong>inline in the page</strong> because
      <code>raise_on_prerender_error = false</code>. You see the error box below the page heading.<br/>
    <% end %>
    <span class="label">Console replay:</span> The <code>console.log</code>, <code>console.warn</code>, and
    <code>console.error</code> calls from the component are replayed in the browser console.<br/>
    <span class="label">errorReporter:</span>
    <%= throw_js_errors ? "Called — the re-thrown error is caught by the Node renderer." : "Not called — throwJsErrors is false." %>
  </div>

  <p>The <code>rescue_from</code> handler in <code>ApplicationController</code>:</p>
  <pre>rescue_from ReactOnRails::PrerenderError do |err|
  if response.committed?
    # Stream already started — write error HTML + JS redirect into stream
    response.stream.write(error_message + js_redirect + meta_refresh)
    response.stream.close
  else
    # Normal redirect (non-streaming path)
    redirect_to server_side_log_throw_raise_invoker_path,
                flash: { error: msg }
  end
end</pre>
</div>

<hr/>

<%# ───────────────────── SECTION 2: STREAMING CLIENT COMPONENT ERRORS ───────────────────── %>

<h2>Section 2: Streaming Client Component Errors (<code>stream_react_component</code>)</h2>

<p>
  These use <code>stream_react_component</code> with client components (not React Server Components).
  These components follow the async-on-server / sync-on-client pattern: on the server they return
  a <code>Promise</code> (enabling streaming via <code>&lt;Suspense&gt;</code>), while on the client
  they return synchronous JSX (for hydration). React&rsquo;s <code>renderToPipeableStream</code>
  handles the streaming, with its <code>onShellError</code> / <code>onError</code> callbacks.
</p>

<div class="scenario">
  <h3>A: SSR Shell Error &mdash; <%= link_to "Open page", ssr_shell_error_path(config_params) %></h3>

  <p><span class="label">Component:</span> <code>StreamShellErrorDemo</code> (synchronous &mdash; no async/client split needed since it throws immediately)</p>
