<%# ───────────────────────────────── SECTION 3: RSC ERRORS ───────────────────────────────── %>

<h2>Section 3: RSC (React Server Component) Errors</h2>

<div class="important-note">
  <strong>Why RSC errors are always &ldquo;post-shell&rdquo;:</strong>
  When a React Server Component is rendered via <code>stream_react_component</code> with
  <code>prerender: true</code>, the HTML rendering pipeline wraps it in:

  <pre>RSCProvider                              &larr; context provider (sync)
  &lt;Suspense fallback={null}&gt;             &larr; Suspense boundary (sync)
    RSCRoute                             &larr; client component (sync)
      PromiseWrapper                     &larr; calls use(promise) &rarr; SUSPENDS
  &lt;/Suspense&gt;</pre>

  <p>React&rsquo;s <code>renderToPipeableStream</code> renders this tree. When it reaches
  <code>PromiseWrapper</code>, <code>use(promise)</code> <strong>suspends</strong> because the RSC
  payload has not resolved yet. React renders the Suspense fallback (<code>null</code>) as the shell content
  and fires <code>onShellReady</code> &mdash; setting <code>isShellReady = true</code>.</p>

  <p>The RSC content resolves asynchronously via the promise. If the server component throws, the
  promise rejects, <code>use()</code> throws inside the Suspense boundary, and React calls
  <code>onError</code> (not <code>onShellError</code>). The resulting JSON chunk has
  <code>isShellReady = true</code>, so Ruby consults
  <code>raise_non_shell_server_rendering_errors</code> (not <code>raise_on_prerender_error</code>).</p>

  <p>This means <strong>even if <code>raise_on_prerender_error = true</code>, RSC component errors will
  not cause Rails to raise</strong> unless <code>raise_non_shell_server_rendering_errors</code> is also
  <code>true</code>.</p>
</div>

